      { heading: 'Why "Same as My Neighbor" Pricing Fails', level: 2 as const, body: 'Walk down a row of kiosks or stalls anywhere from Merkato to a neighborhood market and prices tend to cluster tightly — everyone charges roughly what everyone else charges, because that is the fastest way to avoid losing customers to the stall next door. The trouble is that your neighbor\'s cost structure is not your cost structure. If they buy in larger volume, get better terms from a supplier, or carry less transport cost, they can profit at a price that barely covers your costs. Without knowing your own landed cost per item — purchase price plus transport plus any spoilage allowance — you cannot tell whether matching the market price is smart or slowly draining your capital.' },
      { heading: 'Calculating Real Margin, Not Just Markup', level: 2 as const, body: 'A common trap is confusing markup with margin. If you buy an item for 80 birr and sell it for 100, that looks like a 20 birr profit, but if you lose one in ten to spoilage or breakage, your real margin is thinner once that loss is spread across what you actually sell. Traders who track purchases and sales together, item by item, start to see which products carry genuinely healthy margin and which ones are basically break-even once losses and small discounts to regular customers are factored in. AskBiz logs both the buying side and selling side against the same item, so instead of a vague sense that "this sells well," you see the actual birr profit per item over a week or a month.' },
      { heading: 'Using Real Numbers to Negotiate With Suppliers', level: 2 as const, body: 'Suppliers respect traders who show up with numbers, not complaints. If you can tell a wholesaler at Merkato that you consistently move forty units of a product a week, month after month, you have leverage for a better unit price or better payment terms that a trader who cannot say how much they buy simply does not have. This is one of the most underused benefits of tracking sales digitally — it is not just about knowing your own business, it becomes evidence in a negotiation. A supplier is far more willing to extend a small discount or short credit term to a trader whose order pattern is predictable and provable than to one who orders erratically and cannot say why.' },
      { heading: 'Adjusting Prices Without Losing Customers', level: 2 as const, body: 'Raising prices on regular customers is delicate, especially in markets where relationships matter as much as price. The traders who manage it best make small, item-specific adjustments based on actual margin data rather than blanket increases across everything they sell. If your data shows one item is losing money at the current price while others are healthy, you can raise just that one price, or quietly source it more cheaply, instead of alienating loyal customers with a general price hike. Over time this item-by-item discipline, informed by real numbers instead of a feeling that "prices need to go up," protects both your margin and your customer relationships at the same time.' }
